  pm-2muu,related,"2026-07-03T13:25:54.919Z",null,null
body: "## Context\nFiled by the 2026-07-03 concurrency audit. Stale-lock takeover is check-then-act: two waiters can both classify a lock stale, both unlink, both create — and both believe they own the item; the loser's write is silently overwritten.\n\n## Interleaving\nA reads stale → B reads stale → A unlinks + creates fresh lock → B (holding the OLD stale read) unlinks A's FRESH lock → B creates its own → A and B mutate concurrently. Window opens only when a stale lock (crashed process) is contended by parallel agents — exactly the recovery case the lock exists for.\n\n## Relation to pm-2muu (dep: related)\nThe uncommitted pm-2muu rework folds stale handling into the wait loop and caps removals (MAX_STALE_LOCK_REMOVALS=3), which bounds livelock but does NOT close this race: the unlink target is still not identity-checked.\n\n## Approach\nMake removal identity-safe: only remove the exact lock observed (compare payload/inode — e.g. rename the stale lock to a unique tombstone name and verify, or re-read after create and back off if the payload isn't ours). After createLockFile succeeds following a stale removal, re-read the lock file and verify owner == self; if not, treat as lost and re-enter the wait loop.\n\n## Definition of done\nA deterministic two-waiter stale-lock test (fake clock / injected reads) shows exactly one winner; stress run over crashed-lock scenarios shows no double-grant; evidence recorded here."
